-- historians think of it as
ethnic cleansing. That is
shocking

11:34.227 --> 11:37.764 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
that in 2015 one of our
presidential candidates is
espousing that as his model for
immigration.

11:37.764 --> 11:40.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Josh Blackman, as
you watched and listened to what
they were saying, what

11:40.033 --> 11:43.136 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
leaped out at you?

11:43.136 --> 11:46.940 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOSH BLACKMAN, Constitutional
Law Professor, South Texas
College of Law: So, I think
Marielena

11:46.940 --> 11:49.943 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is correct. It's physically
impossible to remove 11 million
immigrants.

11:49.943 --> 11:53.212 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
But I think the correct
framework is that some sort of
reform has to be passed and that

11:53.212 --> 11:53.279 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this cannot be accomplished
through executive action, which
is what President Obama has

11:53.279 --> 11:54.881 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
done.

11:54.881 --> 11:56.316 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: So, what is it that
you heard last night that
sounded like a reasonable

11:56.316 --> 11:58.217 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
approach?

11:58.217 --> 12:01.788 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOSH BLACKMAN: So, I think
Senator Rubio advanced a
proposal where immigrants who
have been

12:01.788 --> 12:06.125 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
here for a while who have
families and have not gotten in
trouble, had they stayed 10

12:06.125 --> 12:09.762 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
years, there will be a pathway
for some sort of way for them to
remain. And he also suggested

12:09.762 --> 12:11.998 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that certain felons would be
able to be moved primarily.

12:11.998 --> 12:12.899 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Marielena Hincapie,
this week, the Fifth Circuit
Court of Appeals moved to

12:12.899 --> 12:12.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
delay, to block President
Obama's plan to delay
deportation for some people who
are

12:12.966 --> 12:11.431 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
not here legally. Does this --
how does this change the
landscape of the immigration
debate

12:11.431 --> 12:12.999 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
or does it?

12:12.999 --> 12:12.932 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARIELENA HINCAPIE: Well, right
now, the decision was a
devastating decision,
particularly for

12:12.932 --> 12:12.999 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the five million U.S. citizen
children whose parents would
have benefited from DACA.

12:12.999 --> 12:13.032 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it was an expected decision,
so it doesn't quite change
things too much, in the sense

12:13.032 --> 12:12.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that we remain in legal status
quo, legal limbo for these
families. On the other hand,

12:12.966 --> 12:12.999 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
because the Supreme Court is
likely to take this case -- and
we're very glad that the

12:12.999 --> 12:13.232 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Obama administration immediately
said that they would be
appealing -- this is a case

12:13.232 --> 12:13.232 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of national significance which
is likely to be decided just
months before the 2016 election.

12:13.232 --> 12:12.699 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So I think the issue will
continue to be front and center
and probably increase in terms

12:12.699 --> 12:13.199 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of the debates, particularly
in the general election.

12:13.199 --> 12:13.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Josh Blackman, does
this help or hurt your election
year argument?

12:13.466 --> 12:12.565 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOSH BLACKMAN: So, I think the
question is not whether the
Supreme Court will hear it,

12:12.565 --> 12:12.198 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
but when the Supreme
Court will hear it.

12:12.198 --> 12:12.565 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, Marielena is correct.

12:12.565 --> 12:12.699 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: It's definitely
going to happen?

12:12.699 --> 12:13.299 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JOSH BLACKMAN: Oh, it's
definitely going to happen.

12:13.299 --> 12:13.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But it will either happen in May
of 2016 or November of 2016. And
the variable is when

12:13.433 --> 12:13.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the court is able to grant
certiorari, when it's able to
grant review. And this is based

12:13.700 --> 12:13.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
first on when the U.S.
government files their appeal
and second when Texas files
their response.

12:13.466 --> 12:13.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If the process too late, it's
very possible that this process
will be stretched and kicked

12:13.333 --> 12:13.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
until next year, so it would not
even be argued until there's a
new president in office.

12:13.466 --> 12:12.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: There were as many
approaches to the immigration
debate on stage last night

12:12.966 --> 12:14.100 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
as there were candidates.

12:14.100 --> 12:14.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I want to run through a few of
them with you, Marielena
Hincapie, starting with you.

12:14.100 --> 12:13.299 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Jeb Bush talked about fines and
talking as a way of making sure
that people stay -- obey

12:13.299 --> 12:14.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the law. How applicable
can that be?

12:14.200 --> 12:14.067 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARIELENA HINCAPIE: Yes, paying
a penalty has actually been one
of the central factors

12:14.067 --> 12:14.267 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of all of the immigration reform
proposals, legislative proposals
in the past.

12:14.267 --> 12:14.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think Jeb Bush is right that
that is often -- and immigrants
are ready and willing to

12:14.233 --> 12:14.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
pay a fine to be able to stay in
the U.S. to obtain lawful status
and work lawfully

12:14.300 --> 12:14.367 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and not have that fear of
deportations and contribute even
more to our country.

12:14.367 --> 12:14.634 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Josh Blackman, we
have heard much discussion about
the path to citizenship,

12:14.634 --> 12:14.801 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but a lot less discussion than
we used to. People like Jeb Bush
and Marco Rubio, who

12:14.801 --> 12:13.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
used to say -- and even John
Kasich, I think, last night
suggested it -- but it's being

12:13.866 --> 12:14.834 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
talked about a lot
less. Why is that?

12:14.834 --> 12:14.901 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOSH BLACKMAN: I think one of
the factors we have to consider
is the role that President

12:14.901 --> 12:14.801 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Barack Obama's presidential
executive actions played in
chilling congressional reform.

12:14.801 --> 12:15.101 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Speaker Paul Ryan had a piece in
"USA Today" last week
effectively arguing that because

12:15.101 --> 12:15.034 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the president acts unilaterally,
it's harder to trust the
president. I think, in many
respects,

12:15.034 --> 12:17.737 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this unilateral action has made
it more difficult to actually
have some sort of comprehensive

12:17.737 --> 12:19.806 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
immigration reform.

12:19.806 --> 12:21.407 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: You're saying it's
the unilateral action, not the
actual substance of the policy

12:21.407 --> 12:23.009 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
itself?

12:23.009 --> 12:26.980 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOSH BLACKMAN: Well, I think any
discussion of whether you're
actually rewarded people

12:26.980 --> 12:29.015 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
perhaps who enter the country
illegally must be premised on
what President Obama has done

12:29.015 --> 12:31.718 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
previously.

12:31.718 --> 12:35.855 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If in fact the president is
trying to abrogate and bypass
Congress, it makes it less
likely

12:35.855 --> 12:38.725 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that Congress will want to
work with him to move forward.

12:38.725 --> 12:43.029 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Marielena Hincapie,
some people -- Ben Carson is one
of the people who have

12:43.029 --> 12:46.599 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
suggested that perhaps a
guest-worker program might be an
approach. Is that something that

12:46.599 --> 12:50.203 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
you can see happening
that is middle ground?

12:50.203 --> 12:53.406 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARIELENA HINCAPIE: Absolutely
not, not a guest-worker program
by itself.

12:53.406 --> 12:57.977 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think particularly for Ben
Carson and the Republican
candidates who yesterday talked

12:57.977 --> 13:03.282 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about not being in support of
the minimum wage, when we --
when they are thinking of

13:03.282 --> 13:08.388 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
adding guest workers as the
solution to immigration, that
simply is going to depress wages
and

13:08.388 --> 13:11.257 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
working conditions even
more for U.S. workers.

13:11.257 --> 13:16.062 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We need to ensure that the 11
million people who are here who
are already working have

13:16.062 --> 13:20.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a path to citizenship and that
we separately look at what are
the forms, legal channels

13:20.166 --> 13:23.302 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
for people to come
in the future.

13:23.302 --> 13:27.740 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
For current guest-worker
programs, they are extremely
full of exploitation, mainly
because

13:27.740 --> 13:32.879 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
workers are tied to an employer
who can exploit them and unless
those individual workers,

13:32.879 --> 13:38.284 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
those temporary workers have the
same rights as U.S. workers, are
able to leave that work

13:38.284 --> 13:43.089 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and take their visa, have a
portable visa, that guest-worker
programs are just not the

13:43.089 --> 13:46.159 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
answer and not the solution. And
it's definitely not the solution
for the 11 million who are

13:46.159 --> 13:49.762 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
here and who are working and who
have deep ties to our
communities.

13:49.762 --> 13:52.865 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Josh Blackman, what
about the so-called dreamers?
They got their hopes up

13:52.865 --> 13:57.103 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
last year with the idea that
they would be able to stay here
or they could at least apply

13:57.103 --> 14:00.573 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to stay here. Is that going to
fall apart or is that anything
that any of these Republicans

14:00.573 --> 14:02.408 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
are supporting?

14:02.408 --> 14:06.245 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOSH BLACKMAN: So, I think the
senators are opposed -- sorry --
the candidates are opposed

14:06.245 --> 14:07.613 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to DACA. That's Deferred
Action for Childhood Arrivals.

14:07.613 --> 14:09.215 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
GWEN IFILL: Right.

14:09.215 --> 14:12.885 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOSH BLACKMAN: Congress defeated
the DREAM Act and the president
went ahead and enacted

14:12.885 --> 14:16.622 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
not the exact same thing, but
significant portions of it,
through executive action.

14:16.622 --> 14:20.293 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think in many respects,
that, too, that has chilled the
decision of whether Congress

14:20.293 --> 14:23.996 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
can act. And one point I make --
I would like to make on the
timing of the Supreme Court

14:23.996 --> 14:29.001 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
appeal, the Obama administration
had a chance to appeal to the
Supreme Court in May of 2016.

14:29.001 --> 14:31.304 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Their failure to do it basically
ensured that this couldn't be
decided until the earliest

14:31.304 --> 14:33.606 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
of the summer before
the election.

14:33.606 --> 14:37.877 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So whether it is in fact a
priority for the Obama
administration to appeal is not
clear.

14:37.877 --> 14:41.981 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They may be content to let this
sit as a political issue and
have Senator Clinton perhaps and

14:41.981 --> 14:43.750 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the Republican candidate duke
this out. There may be political
elements here in delaying

14:43.750 --> 14:44.951 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the appeal itself.

14:44.951 --> 14:46.486 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Briefly, where
is public opinion on this?

14:46.486 --> 14:47.353 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JOSH BLACKMAN: On?

14:47.353 --> 14:50.056 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: On this whole issue?

14:50.056 --> 14:53.626 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOSH BLACKMAN: Well, I think for
the most part, people are
looking to have a comprehensive

14:53.626 --> 14:56.395 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
reform through Congress and not
through unilateral executive
action.

14:56.395 --> 15:00.299 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: And, Marielena, one
final thought on public opinion.

15:00.299 --> 15:04.370 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARIELENA HINCAPIE: Yes, as
Joshua said, there is a lot of
support. A majority of Americans

15:04.370 --> 15:08.407 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
support both comprehensive
immigration reform through
Congress, but recent polling
actually

15:08.407 --> 15:12.145 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
shows that the majority of
Americans also support the
president's actions.

15:12.145 --> 15:17.083 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
They don't believe that
undocumented immigrants who are
here, who are contributing to
our

15:17.083 --> 15:21.087 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
economy, who have children, who
have deep ties to our country
should be deported either.

15:21.087 --> 15:25.124 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So there is support for the
president's action, as well as
Congress. We -- ultimately, we

15:25.124 --> 15:28.861 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
need Congress to act so that a
future president can sign that
law into -- sign an immigration

15:28.861 --> 15:31.397 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
reform bill into law.

15:31.397 --> 15:35.902 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Marielena Hincapie
of the National Immigration Law
Center and Josh Blackman of

15:35.902 --> 15:37.703 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the South Texas College of
law, thank you both very much.

15:37.703 --> 15:38.771 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JOSH BLACKMAN: Thank
you very much.

15:38.771 --> 15:47.713 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARIELENA HINCAPIE: Thank
you. Thank you, Gwen.

15:47.713 --> 15:56.422 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Playing daily
fantasy sports has become a
multibillion-dollar business,

15:56.422 --> 16:01.761 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and one increasingly connected
with professional sports leagues
who either have a sponsorship

16:01.761 --> 16:06.032 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
deal with the biggest companies
or are investors in these
companies. But it's an industry
under

16:06.032 --> 16:09.035 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
widening scrutiny.

16:09.035 --> 16:13.072 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The latest front: New York
state's attorney general has
said they shouldn't be allowed

16:13.072 --> 16:17.109 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to operate in New York since
they constitute illegal
gambling.

16:17.109 --> 16:19.645 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
William Brangham fills
in the picture.

16:19.645 --> 16:23.716 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The two main
companies at the center of this
latest controversy, DraftKings

16:23.716 --> 16:27.520 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and FanDuel, have tens of
millions of players on their
sites everyday.

16:27.520 --> 16:31.724 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Here's how they work. This is
from one of their promotional
videos. You pay some money

16:31.724 --> 16:36.362 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to play fantasy football or
baseball or whatever sport you
want. You then create a lineup
of

16:36.362 --> 16:41.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
actual professional players to
be part of your fantasy team. If
your players do better

16:41.100 --> 16:43.803 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
statistically on a given day
than the other people in your
league, you win money. Or if

16:43.803 --> 16:46.539 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
they don't, you lose.

16:46.539 --> 16:50.943 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The sites have said they're just
games of online skill, and not
actual gambling. But,

16:50.943 --> 16:54.380 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
yesterday, New York Attorney
General Eric Schneiderman called
foul, saying -- quote

16:54.380 --> 16:59.485 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
-- "It is clear that DraftKings
and FanDuel are the leaders of a
massive, multibillion-dollar

16:59.485 --> 17:04.924 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
scheme intended to evade the law
and fleece sports fans across
the country."

17:04.924 --> 17:07.026 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Joining me now to help unpack
these developments is Devlin
Barrett, who's been covering
this

17:07.026 --> 17:08.828 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
for The Wall Street Journal.

17:08.828 --> 17:11.797 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, how big a deal is this,
the attorney general's move?

17:11.797 --> 17:13.799 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DEVLIN BARRETT, The Wall Street
Journal: It's a really big deal.

17:13.799 --> 17:17.403 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One, it's 10 percent of their
customer base is based in New
York state. But, actually...

17:17.403 --> 17:20.172 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Ten percent of
all these players are in New
York itself?

17:20.172 --> 17:24.043 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DEVLIN BARRETT: That's according
to some of the internal figures,
as best as we can tell.

17:24.043 --> 17:31.417 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The larger problem, though, is
that if what the New York
attorney general says influences

17:31.417 --> 17:36.656 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or lines up with the thinking of
the federal officials who are
looking at this, these
companies,

17:36.656 --> 17:39.392 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this industry is in a world of
trouble, because what the
attorney general says in his
letter

17:39.392 --> 17:44.597 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
is that this thing is
illegal in multiple ways.

17:44.597 --> 17:48.467 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the Justice Department is
looking at that. Now, the New
York decision is important for

17:48.467 --> 17:53.539 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
New York, and it's important,
obviously, for the company's
reputations, but if the U.S.

17:53.539 --> 17:57.410 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
attorney for the Southern
District of New York, who's a
federal official, ends up
agreeing

17:57.410 --> 17:59.812 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with even half of what's in that
letter, these industries are in
huge -- this industry has

17:59.812 --> 18:01.814 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a huge problem.

18:01.814 --> 18:05.885 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Let's talk a
little bit about what the
attorney general is arguing.

18:05.885 --> 18:10.189 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In one of his complaints against
these companies, he is saying,
you're basically a wolf in
sheep's

