the curiosity.

28:33.378 --> 28:36.915 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So this is the
same instinct that we have
today, to look around the next

28:36.915 --> 28:38.483 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
corner, over the next hill.

28:38.483 --> 28:40.118 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
DAVID LORDKIPANIDZE:
Paul is doing the same.

28:40.118 --> 28:42.020 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN:
As these guys did.

28:42.020 --> 28:45.290 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID LORDKIPANIDZE: As these
guys did. Paul is follower of
Homo erectus.

28:45.290 --> 28:47.125 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

28:47.125 --> 28:50.996 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And, in a
sense, so are we all. But for
Salopek, their ancient journey

28:50.996 --> 28:54.132 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to this point has
particular meaning.

28:54.132 --> 28:57.469 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SALOPEK: These are the
first pioneer wanderers. These
are kind of like the dawn

28:57.469 --> 29:03.241 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
people who first left our
collective home in Africa. So
being here is a terrific echo

29:03.241 --> 29:08.480 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of my own project. I'm following
people who came much later, but
these were the trailblazers.

29:08.480 --> 29:12.551 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Only 10
percent of this sprawling site
has been excavated. That layered

29:12.551 --> 29:13.819 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
effect was evident everywhere.

29:13.819 --> 29:17.089 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, where are you taking me?

29:17.089 --> 29:21.593 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In a deep pit, David showed us
where an ancient wine maker had
sunk his vat.

29:21.593 --> 29:24.262 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID LORDKIPANIDZE: You can
see 1.8 million years old.

29:24.262 --> 29:26.999 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The bone
is 1.8 million years old.

29:26.999 --> 29:31.570 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, in the process, that person
had tossed aside some of the
much older bones.

29:31.570 --> 29:33.071 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
This wine jar is how old?

29:33.071 --> 29:36.274 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
DAVID LORDKIPANIDZE:
It's a 1,000 years old.

29:36.274 --> 29:38.377 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: You know,
finding a 1,000-year wine jar
would be kind of a big deal for
anybody

29:38.377 --> 29:39.277 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
else.

29:39.277 --> 29:40.379 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
DAVID LORDKIPANIDZE: Not
for a paleontologist.

29:40.379 --> 29:42.314 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

29:42.314 --> 29:47.285 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: But there are
few better places for a writer
gauging the crosscurrents

29:47.285 --> 29:52.758 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of history. So, with sunset not
far off, Paul and I walked to
the top of the citadel that

29:52.758 --> 29:58.430 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
has stood here for 1,000 years,
a relative blink of an eye
geologically speaking, the

29:58.430 --> 30:02.701 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
majesty of this place clear,
spread out before us, and
perhaps a key to its fraught and
important

30:02.701 --> 30:04.469 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
past.

30:04.469 --> 30:07.973 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So, why is this place
such a crossroads?

30:07.973 --> 30:13.145 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SALOPEK: Well, it's an
antique bridge between Asia and
Europe and has been for
millennia.

30:13.145 --> 30:20.018 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And there has been migration
routes through here going back
before memory.

30:20.018 --> 30:25.557 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The silk road passes through
here. But it also is the
epicenter where three major
empires

30:25.557 --> 30:32.397 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
meet. And they have always
contested this area. From the
south, the Persians, from the

30:32.397 --> 30:37.969 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
West, the Ottoman Empire, which
is today Turkey, and from the
north, more recently, Russia.

30:37.969 --> 30:42.207 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
They have overlapped and
contested and fought over this
corner of the world for
centuries.

30:42.207 --> 30:44.843 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, if they
have lived here, they have also
died here.

30:44.843 --> 30:47.112 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SALOPEK: A lot of people
have died here over the years. I
think we're standing on

30:47.112 --> 30:50.315 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
one of the oldest
boneyards in the world.

30:50.315 --> 30:52.951 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Atop the
boneyard in Dmanisi, Georgia,
I'm Hari Sreenivasan for the
"PBS

30:52.951 --> 30:54.920 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
NewsHour."

30:54.920 --> 30:59.825 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Paul Salopek has
continued walking since Hari
caught up with him in Georgia.

30:59.825 --> 31:03.228 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
He's now crossed
into Azerbaijan.

31:03.228 --> 31:06.998 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Salopek's work is supported in
part by the Pulitzer Center for
Crisis Reporting, which

31:06.998 --> 31:10.102 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
also partners with
the "NewsHour."

31:10.102 --> 31:13.705 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For more on Salopek's walk,
including some of Hari's photos
and thoughts, head online

31:13.705 --> 31:21.580 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to our site at PBS.org/NewsHour.

31:21.580 --> 31:36.895 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Parents and
plenty of 20- and 30-somethings
are well aware that many young

31:36.895 --> 31:41.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
adults move back home these
days after they finish school.

31:41.266 --> 31:46.471 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But a new analysis of census
data out today from the Pew
Research Center underlines the

31:46.471 --> 31:52.110 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
extent to which this is
happening. It finds that 36
percent of women between the
ages

31:52.110 --> 31:59.151 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of 18 and 34 are living at home
with parents or relatives.
That's higher than at any time

31:59.151 --> 32:05.290 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
since 1940. An earlier analysis
also found that nearly 43
percent of young men lived

32:05.290 --> 32:08.927 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
in a similar
arrangement last year.

32:08.927 --> 32:14.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Let's break down some of these
findings with Richard Fry. He
wrote today's analysis for

32:14.366 --> 32:18.470 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Pew. And Gillian White, she is
with "The Atlantic" and writes
frequently about the lives of
millennials.

32:18.470 --> 32:21.940 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And we welcome you
both to the program.

32:21.940 --> 32:27.345 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, Richard Fry, 36 percent,
more than 36 percent, the
biggest percentage we have seen

32:27.345 --> 32:30.482 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
since the Great Depression,
what's behind this?

32:30.482 --> 32:32.951 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RICHARD FRY, Pew Research
Center: I would then point to
sort of three factors sort of

32:32.951 --> 32:36.588 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
through the long-run sweep.

32:36.588 --> 32:43.094 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's -- the low point was about
1960, where about 24 percent. So
it's been on the rise

32:43.094 --> 32:48.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
slowly, markedly picked up in
the new century. Three factors.
Number one, young adults are

32:48.033 --> 32:53.505 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
much less likely to be married
than was the case 50, 60 years
ago.

32:53.505 --> 32:59.611 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When young couples get married,
they don't live with their
parents. So that delayed
marriage

32:59.611 --> 33:04.649 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
has sort of reduced the
incentive to leave the nest.
Secondly, particularly among
young

33:04.649 --> 33:09.154 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
women, many more of them are
college students. College
enrollment by young women has
gone

33:09.154 --> 33:13.658 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
up about five-fold since 1960.

33:13.658 --> 33:17.596 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
College students, if you think
about community college
students, students going to
local

33:17.596 --> 33:21.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
universities, much more likely
to be living at home. And then,
finally, particularly since

33:21.600 --> 33:26.638 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the 1970s, young adults have
become more racially and
ethnically diverse as a result
of increased

33:26.638 --> 33:28.907 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
immigration.

33:28.907 --> 33:35.680 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What we know is that young
adults from minority backgrounds
are more likely to live with
parents

33:35.680 --> 33:41.219 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
than white young adults. And so
as young adults have become more
diverse, more of them are

33:41.219 --> 33:43.622 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
living at home.

33:43.622 --> 33:46.758 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Family patterns,
more multigenerational
households.

33:46.758 --> 33:50.595 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And just quickly, for young
men, some of the same reasons?

33:50.595 --> 33:54.032 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RICHARD FRY: Yes, yes. And they
-- young men have followed a
very similar trend.

33:54.032 --> 33:58.737 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, let me --
before I turned to you, Gillian
White, let me -- we put out

33:58.737 --> 34:04.876 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a call out on social media today
asking young people, if you're
living at home with family

34:04.876 --> 34:08.980 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
or relatives, tell us about the
factors that led you to do this.

34:08.980 --> 34:12.550 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And here are two quick comments,
one from Facebook. Now, this
comes from a woman named

34:12.550 --> 34:17.322 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Janis Smith. She says: "My
college-educated 30-year-old
daughter lives at home with her

34:17.322 --> 34:22.127 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
parents because her public
school salary is too low for her
to fully support herself and

34:22.127 --> 34:24.696 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
her 1-year-old son."

34:24.696 --> 34:30.669 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then from Twitter, we got
this comment from Steffanie
Ybanez. She tweeted: "I'm 25,

34:30.669 --> 34:35.106 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
living at home, still in
college, plan to stay at home
after graduation to save money

34:35.106 --> 34:38.543 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and pay off loans."

34:38.543 --> 34:45.750 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, Angela -- I mean, so,
Gillian -- I'm sorry -- do these
sound like common reasons?
You're

34:45.750 --> 34:47.319 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
hearing -- you have been
reporting on this generation for
some time.

34:47.319 --> 34:48.720 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
GILLIAN WHITE, "The
Atlantic": Yes.

34:48.720 --> 34:53.024 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think these two comments
really illustrate a lot that we
hear when it comes to finance

34:53.024 --> 34:57.228 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and economics and why people are
staying at home. The first piece
is that wages have not

34:57.228 --> 35:01.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
seen a ton of growth, especially
for young people, since the end
of the recession. The

35:01.733 --> 35:05.537 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
economy is getting better, but
wages haven't really
skyrocketed.

35:05.537 --> 35:11.142 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, if you still feel like you
might have a difficult time
paying rent, paying utilities,

35:11.142 --> 35:15.480 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
paying for all these other
things, it might feel safer to
just go ahead and stay home.

35:15.480 --> 35:20.685 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In addition to that, we know
that student loan debt loads are
rising, so a lot of people

35:20.685 --> 35:25.190 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are saying, until I can get a
handle on my finances, until I
can pay down these debts,

35:25.190 --> 35:28.326 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
maybe I should just stay at home
with my parents, where I can
either pay a nominal amount or

35:28.326 --> 35:32.430 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
pay nothing and really
catch up on my finances.

35:32.430 --> 35:38.269 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And what about,
Richard Fry, in your looking at
the data, does it back

35:38.269 --> 35:40.338 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this up? Because the economy, if
you step back and look at the
economics, it's supposed

35:40.338 --> 35:41.373 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to have gotten better.

35:41.373 --> 35:43.775 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
RICHARD FRY: Yes.

35:43.775 --> 35:47.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I did a report about three
months ago where I very much
just sort of focused on
recently,

35:47.746 --> 35:54.819 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
since the great recession, and
what's been happening. And from
2007 to 2010, when the

35:54.819 --> 35:59.858 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
economy was sinking, more young
adults lived at home. The
expectation -- and it was my

35:59.858 --> 36:05.430 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
expectation and others'
expectations -- that after 2010,
as the job market started to
improve

36:05.430 --> 36:10.869 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and unemployment rates came
down, that young adults would
start leaving the nest.

36:10.869 --> 36:14.606 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Young adult employment rates
have come down. More of them do
have jobs. There is even some

36:14.606 --> 36:17.976 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
evidence that their earnings are
starting to rise, at least a
little bit. And yet more

36:17.976 --> 36:22.514 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of them are living at home than
was the case five years ago.

36:22.514 --> 36:26.418 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so it's not altogether clear
how much the job market and
what's going on in the

36:26.418 --> 36:29.487 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
job market for young
adults is driving this.

36:29.487 --> 36:32.023 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, Gillian
White, in your reporting -- and,
again, you have been looking

36:32.023 --> 36:34.092 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
at this for some time -- what
do you think is going on here?

36:34.092 --> 36:37.395 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
GILLIAN WHITE: I mean, I
think it's two pieces.

36:37.395 --> 36:41.399 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think, even if things get
better, I think people really
have it in their heads,
especially

36:41.399 --> 36:47.005 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
young people, that finances are
a problem, that maybe jobs
aren't as secure as they once

36:47.005 --> 36:51.409 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
were. So they are a little
hesitant to maybe move out on
their own in case something
happens.

36:51.409 --> 36:56.181 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think, other than that -- and
this is anecdotal largely, but
it could be that cultural norms

36:56.181 --> 37:01.586 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have changed. A few years ago, a
few decades ago, having a
30-year-old who lived at home

37:01.586 --> 37:07.258 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
might have raised some eyebrows,
but now not as much, because we
have that excuse of the

37:07.258 --> 37:10.995 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
great recession, we have that
excuse of student loan debt, we
have that excuse of the economy.

37:10.995 --> 37:15.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And I did some
reporting on millennials eight
or nine years ago, and at

37:15.600 --> 37:20.205 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that point, and this was the --
this cohort, but younger, and
what we found then is, they

37:20.205 --> 37:24.909 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
were closer to their parents
than any young generation had
been in history.

37:24.909 --> 37:27.812 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, are you picking up, Gillian,
any of that in what you're...

37:27.812 --> 37:28.279 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

37:28.279 --> 37:30.315 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
GILLIAN WHITE: Yes, absolutely.

37:30.315 --> 37:35.920 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
I think the feeling of a
cultural shift occurs both for
millennials and for their boomer

37:35.920 --> 37:40.291 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
parents, where a lot of those
parents aren't really trying to
push them out. They are happy

37:40.291 --> 37:45.463 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to have them home. They are
happy to kind of feel young and
have somebody around to

37:45.463 --> 37:50.068 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
teach them about new technology,
and kids aren't feeling as
alienated from their parents.

37:50.068 --> 37:53.972 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So the idea of staying home with
them doesn't feel as awful.

37:53.972 --> 37:58.743 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Richard Fry,
looking -- I know how this is --
it's hard to project into the

37:58.743 --> 38:03.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
future, but can you see any
patterns in the past when
something like this has
happened?

38:03.348 --> 38:07.085 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How long does it take before it
shifts, or does it shift? I
mean, could this be the way

38:07.085 --> 38:08.920 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
it's going to be?

38:08.920 --> 38:16.761 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RICHARD FRY: I think that there
is some sense that this may be,
in some ways, a new normal.

38:16.761 --> 38:21.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And what I mean by that is, we
know, for example, that the
racial ethnic diversification is

38:21.633 --> 38:29.374 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
likely to continue, OK? We also
know that the job market cannot
get a whole lot better

38:29.374 --> 38:34.045 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
than sort of where we're at. I
mean, the national unemployment
rate is now down to 5 percent.

38:34.045 --> 38:37.382 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So if you think it's all about
the job market, it's not clear
that the job market can get

38:37.382 --> 38:43.421 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a whole lot better. No one
really knows. But I do think
that a return to the levels of

38:43.421 --> 38:47.525 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the early '60s is probably not
in the cards anytime soon.

38:47.525 --> 38:50.929 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The new normal.
All right, we are going to get
used to this.

38:50.929 --> 38:56.501 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Richard Fry, Gillian
White, thank you.

38:56.501 --> 39:02.874 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
GILLIAN WHITE: Thanks.

39:02.874 --> 39:10.915 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: He is the elusive
older brother, who even Sherlock
Holmes claimed was smarter

39:10.915 --> 39:13.384 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
than he.

39:13.384 --> 39:17.922 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
"Mycroft Holmes" is the title of
the latest addition to the
"NewsHour" Bookshelf. Its

39:17.922 --> 39:24.562 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
