41:09.734 --> 41:14.172 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, London was attached to all
of its colonies, so that
attachment really hasn't been
explored.

41:14.172 --> 41:19.844 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: What explains the
fascination with Sherlock Holmes
that continues, the books,

41:19.844 --> 41:25.083 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the movies, the popular PBS
television, and now you? What
explains that?

41:25.083 --> 41:29.654 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KAREEM ABDUL-JABBAR: People want
to see crime detection done in a
way where we get it right.

41:29.654 --> 41:30.755 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
There's too many times...

41:30.755 --> 41:33.124 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Where
we get it right?

41:33.124 --> 41:37.061 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KAREEM ABDUL-JABBAR: Where we
get it correct. We identify the
bad guys and either incarcerate

41:37.061 --> 41:40.798 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and punish them or get
them out of the picture.

41:40.798 --> 41:43.768 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we want the innocent people
to go free. And Sherlock is the
only person that gets

41:43.768 --> 41:44.569 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
it right every time.

41:44.569 --> 41:46.537 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

41:46.537 --> 41:53.211 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KAREEM ABDUL-JABBAR: So, I think
we all want a Sherlock in our
lives in terms of the way

41:53.211 --> 41:58.149 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that our police and crime
detection people work, that they
get it right, and not --
understand

41:58.149 --> 42:01.452 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
who the criminals are and
don't punish the innocent.

42:01.452 --> 42:04.489 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And he does it,
of course, through mental
deduction.

42:04.489 --> 42:09.994 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KAREEM ABDUL-JABBAR: Yes,
through deduction and a careful
analysis of the facts.

42:09.994 --> 42:16.834 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Sherlock is a genius,
literally, at understanding the
facts, and relating them in a
way that

42:16.834 --> 42:20.004 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
he figures out what's going on.

42:20.004 --> 42:24.041 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: What about your
own fascination with Sherlock
Holmes? There is a fascinating

42:24.041 --> 42:28.679 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
author's note at the end of the
novel in which you say that you
first read the Sherlock Holmes

42:28.679 --> 42:34.419 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
stories early in your basketball
career and adapted Holmes'
powers of observation to the

42:34.419 --> 42:38.189 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
game in order to gain an
edge over your opponents.

42:38.189 --> 42:39.924 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Explain that to me.

42:39.924 --> 42:45.062 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KAREEM ABDUL-JABBAR: By being
able to see into everything in
depth, Sherlock always

42:45.062 --> 42:48.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
has an advantage over
the people around him.

42:48.166 --> 42:52.970 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
